-- Japan, China, India and Thailand: Asian Local Bonds and Currency Previews
-- B y   F r a n c e s   Y o o n
-- 2010-11-11T21:52:50Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-11/japan-china-india-and-thailand-asian-local-bonds-and-currency-previews.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Bond yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary Yoshito Sengoku and Finance
Minister Yoshihiko Noda will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Sengoku will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 1.005 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 82.51 per dollar at 8:44 a.m. in Sydney.  China: Agricultural Development Bank will sell 15 billion
yuan ($2.3 billion) of five-year floaters.  China will sell 10 billion yuan of 182-day bills and 30.7
billion yuan of three- and five-year municipal bonds.  The yield on the 2.53 percent note due June 2015 was 3.64
percent. The yuan was at 6.6233.  India: The statistics office will say industrial production
rose 6.4 percent in September from a year earlier, after rising
5.6 percent the previous month, according to a Bloomberg survey.  India will sell 40 billion rupees ($903 million) of bonds
due 2017, 40 billion rupees of debt maturing in 2020, and 30
billion rupees of 30-year bonds.  The yield on the 7.8 percent bond due May 2020 was 8.09
percent. The rupee was at 44.3075.  Thailand: The Bank of Thailand will announce foreign-
exchange reserves for the week ended Nov. 5. The central bank
said reserves rose to $171.1 billion the previous week.  The Bank of Thailand will sell 85 billion baht ($2.9
billion) of 14-day bills.  The yield on the 5.85 percent note due March 2021 was 3.53
percent. The baht was at 29.76 .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Frances Yoon in Seoul at 
 fyoon2@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
